>

  <h1>Introduction to Ray Marching</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    A rendering technique with no meshes, no triangles — just a function that
    measures distance to the nearest surface.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Prerequisites:</strong> basic linear algebra (vectors, dot product)
    and a browser that supports WebGL 2. No GPU experience required.
  </div>

  <h2>What is ray marching?</h2>

  <p>
    Classical ray tracing finds intersections by solving analytic equations —
    a ray against a triangle, a sphere, a plane. Ray marching takes a different
    approach: instead of solving for the exact intersection, it <em>steps</em>
    along the ray until it gets close enough.
  </p>

  <p>
    What makes it powerful is the stepping strategy. At each point
    <code>p</code> along the ray, we evaluate a <strong>signed distance
    function</strong> (SDF) — a function that returns the shortest distance
    from <code>p</code> to any surface in the scene. Because that distance is a
    safe step size (we cannot hit a surface before walking that far), we can
    jump forward without overshooting. This is called <strong>sphere
    tracing</strong>.
  </p>

  <h3>The algorithm</h3>

  <pre><code>// March a ray from origin ro in direction rd.
// Returns the distance to the first hit, or -1 on miss.
float march(vec3 ro, vec3 rd) &#123;
  float t = 0.0;
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; MAX_STEPS; i++) &#123;
    vec3  p = ro + rd * t;
    float d = scene(p);        // SDF of the whole scene
    if (d &lt; EPSILON)  return t; // hit — close enough
    if (t &gt; MAX_DIST) return -1.0; // miss — too far
    t += d;                    // safe step forward
  &#125;
  return -1.0;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <p>
    The elegance here is that <code>scene(p)</code> can be arbitrarily complex —
    it can combine dozens of primitives, twist and distort space, and still be
    evaluated at a single point with no mesh data.
  </p>

  <h2>Your first ray marched sphere</h2>

  <p>
    The SDF for a sphere centered at the origin with radius <code>r</code> is
    simply <code>length(p) - r</code>. Below is a complete, minimal ray marcher
    rendering a single sphere with Lambertian shading. The normal is estimated
    by sampling the SDF at six nearby points — the <em>central differences</em>
    method.
  </p>

  <ShaderCanvas
    src={helloSphere}
    height={400}
    caption="A sphere rendered entirely in a fragment shader via sphere tracing."
  />

  <p>
    Every pixel is independent — the GPU runs this fragment shader for each one
    in parallel, casting a ray from the virtual camera through that pixel's
    position on the image plane.
  </p>

  <h2>Surface normals</h2>

  <p>
    Because we have an SDF, normals are free. The gradient of a distance field
    at any surface point equals the outward normal. We approximate it with
    central differences — six SDF samples at offset positions:
  </p>

  <pre><code>vec3 normal(vec3 p) &#123;
  vec2 e = vec2(0.001, 0.0);
  return normalize(vec3(
    scene(p + e.xyy) - scene(p - e.xyy),
    scene(p + e.yxy) - scene(p - e.yxy),
    scene(p + e.yyx) - scene(p - e.yyx)
  ));
&#125;</code></pre>

  <p>
    This costs six extra SDF evaluations per hit point. For complex scenes,
    <em>tetrahedron sampling</em> achieves similar quality with four evaluations.
  </p>

</Article>
